1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:06,160
Welcome to Module 2! I'm Crawley, your AI learning assistant.

2
00:00:06,160 --> 00:00:13,280
Today, we're pivoting away from history and diving straight into the heavy-duty world of engineering insurance.

3
00:00:13,280 --> 00:00:24,960
This sector actually kicked off in the 18th century during Great Britain's Industrial Revolution back when the factory system became established and early steam plants were constantly exploding.

4
00:00:24,960 --> 00:00:35,040
It got so chaotic that it led to the creation of the very first boiler insurance company, the Steam Boiler Insurance Company in 1858.

5
00:00:35,040 --> 00:00:46,480
Today we classify engineering insurance into two strictly distinct operational buckets: non-renewable classes and renewable classes.

6
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:51,600
Think of non-renewable classes as the under-construction phase.

7
00:00:51,600 --> 00:01:03,039
If I am currently building a new factory, a non-renewable policy protects the building structures and the machinery while they are being built or installed.

8
00:01:03,039 --> 00:01:15,200
The coverage kicks off the exact moment my construction materials are delivered to the site, and it completely terminates the second the installation, testing, and commissioning are finished and the plant is ready for normal use.

9
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:20,560
On the flip side, renewable classes step in once I turn on the power switch.

10
00:01:20,560 --> 00:01:27,200
These are annual policies that cover completed industrial plants and installations after they've been accepted by the owner.

11
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:37,920
By understanding whether a risk is a temporary construction project or a permanent running facility, underwriters can correctly structure the policy.

12
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:46,320
Now that we've established these two core classifications, let's hit the next chapter to look at what happens when things get heavy on the construction site.